  "edits": [
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its decentralized nome-based militia system created competitive resilience, unlike peer-polity mercenary armies\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom relied on nome-level javelin-and-shield militias that competed for royal patronage; when one nome's forces were defeated, others independently repelled invaders, unlike Mycenaean wanax-led chariot levies or Hittite mercenary bands that collapsed with a single command failure\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Mitanni\", \"Kassite Babylonia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Egyptian nome militias were centrally conscripted and deployed as a unified royal army under Ramesses III, not autonomous units\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Mitanni had a decentralized feudal chariot system with independent city-state contingents analogous to nome militias\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian military under Ramesses III faced identical invasion pressures but with identical institutional responses to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Military-institutional comparison; deliberately atypical in applying competitive federalism to Bronze Age survival. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its Nilotic hydrological unity enabled rapid political recentralization after shocks, unlike peer polities fragmented by geography\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom's dependence on a single, navigable Nile corridor allowed any surviving administrative center to quickly reassert control over the entire valley after local collapses; Mycenaean and Hittite territories, divided by mountains and disconnected river systems, could not be reintegrated once a regional palace fell\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Mesopotamia\", \"Indus Valley\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"The Nile's cataracts and Delta branches created disconnected hydrological zones that fragmented Egyptian administration during the New Kingdom\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Mesopotamia's canal networks provided a comparable unifying hydrological infrastructure to the Nile\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Egyptian recentralization after shocks was driven by military conquest, not hydrological determinism\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Geographic-determinist variant; substitutes mechanism from institutional redundancy to hydrological unity. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its scribal elite formed a self-reproducing epistemic community that preserved administrative knowledge across dynastic ruptures, unlike peer polities' dependent literati\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom's scribal schools, tied to temple scriptoria rather than individual courts, maintained a trans-dynastic curriculum of bureaucratic practice; when a pharaonic house fell, literate administrators seamlessly served successors, whereas Mycenaean Linear B scribes and Hittite court clerks vanished with their patron kings\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Ugarit\", \"Kassite Babylonia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Egyptian scribal training was exclusively tied to the royal court and collapsed during the late New Kingdom\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Ugaritic scribal schools maintained a multi-lingual curriculum independent of royal patronage\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III responded to invasion with identical institutional adaptations as peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Epistemic-community variant; substitutes mechanism from economic redistribution to knowledge transmission. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its polycentric cultic landscape diffused political legitimacy, preventing any single conquest from decapitating the state, unlike peer polities with unitary divine kingship\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom distributed sacral authority across Theban Amun, Memphite Ptah, and Heliopolitan Ra, each capable of anointing a rival pharaoh; when Libyans or Sea Peoples seized one cult center, alternative priesthoods legitimated resistance, whereas Mycenaean wanax ideology and Hittite royal cults concentrated legitimacy in a single figure whose death or capture dissolved the polity\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Minoan Crete\", \"Levantine city-states\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"The Amun priesthood monopolized royal legitimation during the New Kingdom, creating a single point of ideological failure\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Minoan Crete maintained multiple peak sanctuaries that diffused sacral authority across the island\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III faced identical institutional challenges and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Ideological-diffusion variant; swaps economic redistribution for polycentric sacral legitimation. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its grain storage and famine-relief infrastructure functioned as a systemic risk-absorber, unlike peer polities' extractive palace granaries\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom maintained a network of dispersed, temple-managed granaries that released reserves during local harvest failures, stabilizing population and preventing the cascade of debt-slavery and administrative collapse seen in Mycenaean and Hittite systems where centralized palace stores served elite consumption rather than popular welfare\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Minoan Crete\", \"Kassite Babylonia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Egyptian temple granaries primarily served cultic and elite needs, not popular welfare, during the New Kingdom\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Minoan Crete maintained a network of villa-based storage facilities that buffered against local crop failures\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III experienced identical pressures and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Subsistence-security variant; substitutes redistribution mechanism for grain-storage welfare function. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its provincial governors were rotated and monitored through a bureaucratic audit system, preventing the centrifugal fragmentation that destroyed peer polities\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom employed a professionalized nomarch system with regular transfers, dual reporting to vizier and temple, and periodic treasury audits, ensuring provincial elites could not entrench local power bases; in contrast, Mycenaean lawagetas and Hittite vassal kings developed hereditary fiefdoms that seceded or collapsed under external pressure\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Mitanni\", \"Middle Assyria\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"New Kingdom nomarchs were hereditary nobles with entrenched local power, not rotated bureaucrats\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Mitanni maintained a comparable system of rotating provincial governors under central audit\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III faced identical pressures and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Administrative-control variant; substitutes temple-network mechanism for bureaucratic rotation and audit. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its polytheistic pantheon allowed ritual absorption of foreign deities, converting potential cultural threats into integrative resources, unlike peer polities' exclusive state cults\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom incorporated Levantine and Nubian gods (Baal, Astarte, Dedun) into Egyptian temples as subordinate aspects of Amun-Ra, co-opting immigrant communities and frontier populations; Mycenaean and Hittite state cults lacked this absorptive capacity, treating foreign cults as pollutants to be suppressed, which alienated subject peoples and hastened fragmentation\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Mittani\", \"Kassite Babylonia\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Egyptian religion was exclusive and xenophobic, rejecting foreign deities during the New Kingdom\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Hittite state actively incorporated conquered peoples' gods into its pantheon through syncretism\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III faced identical pressures and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Religious-absorptive variant; substitutes economic redistribution for cultic syncretism as resilience mechanism. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its demographic core in Upper Egypt was insulated from Sea Peoples' naval raids, unlike peer polities whose capitals lay exposed on the coast\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom's political and agricultural heartland stretched from Thebes to Memphis along a riverine corridor hundreds of kilometers from the Mediterranean; when Sea Peoples destroyed coastal Levantine and Aegean centers, Egypt's interior remained untouched, whereas Mycenaean palaces at Pylos and Tiryns and the Hittite capital Hattusa lay within raiding distance of the sea or exposed frontiers\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Cyprus\", \"Levantine city-states\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"The Nile Delta, Egypt's administrative and agricultural core, was directly exposed to Sea Peoples' naval attacks\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Cyprus maintained inland administrative centers insulated from coastal raiding\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III faced identical pressures and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Geographic-insulation variant; substitutes institutional mechanism for spatial-demographic buffering. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    },
    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"Egypt survived because its corvée labor system enabled rapid post-crisis infrastructure repair, unlike peer polities dependent on slave or mercenary labor that dissolved under shock\", \"mechanism\": \"The New Kingdom's universal corvée obligation, sanctified by ma'at ideology, allowed any surviving administration to mobilize mass labor for dike repair, canal clearance, and fortification rebuilding immediately after invasions or Nile failures; Mycenaean and Hittite systems relied on enslaved captives or paid specialists whose supply chains collapsed precisely when labor was most needed\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Egypt\", \"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\"], \"excludes\": [\"Kassite Babylonia\", \"Mitanni\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Egyptian corvée was limited to agricultural labor on royal estates and could not be redirected to infrastructure repair\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Kassite Babylonia maintained a comparable universal labor obligation for canal maintenance\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The Egyptian state under Ramesses III faced identical pressures and responded identically to peer polities\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Labor-mobilization variant; substitutes redistribution mechanism for corvée-based infrastructure resilience. Requires Egypt as controlled exception.\"}"
    }
